# streaming_summary.flow — corpus flow #20 of 20.
# See ../../../CORPUS_PLAN.md for the rubric this file is scored against.
#
# Final shape stress test. This flow exists to surface the STREAMING
# / PARTIAL-RESULTS shape: the consumer sees a sequence of typed
# events arriving over time, not one return value at the end.
#
# Context-setting note before the friction marks: the rubric's
# pre-prediction expected #6 (streaming) to surface in exactly ONE
# flow — this one. It has actually surfaced ORGANICALLY in:
#   flow #9   onboard_by_tier (activation events emit per step)
#   flow #15  incident_response (searcher results stream to UI)
#   flow #16  product_search (facet counts stream alongside hits)
#   flow #17  long_running_research (per-step progress events)
#   flow #18  iterative_refinement (per-iteration draft + critique)
#   flow #19  recursive_decomposition (tree fills in left-to-right)
# Six organic occurrences plus this dedicated stress is the
# single most-undercounted prediction in the whole table.
# Streaming is not a niche shape; it is the default shape for any
# flow longer than ~5 seconds.
#
# Shape source: Anthropic streaming API (SSE; named events:
# message_start, content_block_start with tool_use type,
# content_block_delta with partial_json chunks, content_block_stop;
# dual-path architecture — accumulator path with mutable snapshot,
# builder path with immutable typed events). OpenAI streaming
# (tool-call deltas, finish reasons, SSE protocol). Perplexity's
# real-time UX (text streams; citation markers `[1]`, `[2]` inline;
# source URLs arrive in `search_results` output items as discovered).
#
# A streaming-summary workflow has this shape:
#
#   open stream      consumer opens an SSE connection
#                    server begins computing the answer
#
#   emit deltas      as each token / chunk / typed event becomes
#                    available, server EMITS it to the consumer
#                    consumer renders as deltas arrive
#                    events are typed:
#                      ContentDelta {text}
#                      ToolCall {name, partial_json}
#                      CitationDiscovered {marker, source_url}
#                      Usage {tokens_so_far}
#                      MessageStop {finish_reason}
#                      Error {message, recoverable}
#                    (these are precisely the SSE events Anthropic
#                     and OpenAI ship — direct evidence the variant
#                     case is the production case)
#
#   backpressure     consumer may be slow (network, render);
#                    producer checks write-buffer drain, waits
#                    when downstream is full
#
#   cancellation     consumer can abort mid-stream:
#                      "if the model goes off-track, the user or
#                       code can abort mid-stream, and without
#                       streaming you pay for the full generation
#                       whether you use it or not"
#                    server stops computing AND BILLING
#
#   mid-stream err   model errors after partial output already sent:
#                      what about the bytes the consumer has?
#                      what about already-cited sources?
#                      cleanup semantics matter
#
#   close            terminal event arrives:
#                      MessageStop {finish_reason}: "stop" |
#                                                   "max_tokens" |
#                                                   "tool_use" |
#                                                   "error"
#                    consumer ends the stream
#
# Three load-bearing facts:
#
#   (a) The RETURN TYPE is wrong. Flow today says `flow X(I) -> O`
#       returns ONE value of type O at the end. Streaming says
#       `flow X(I) -> Stream<Event>` emits MANY values of type
#       Event over time. This is not a syntax adjustment — it is a
#       different runtime model. Generator-shaped flows do not
#       compose with regular flows the same way; the runtime must
#       support yield-and-suspend. LangGraph, Anthropic SDK, OpenAI
#       SDK all expose streaming as a FIRST-CLASS feature with its
#       own type discipline. Flow does not, and the prediction
#       table missed how often this matters.
#
#   (b) Events are STRUCTURALLY VARIANT, mirroring the sum-type
#       finding of flows #10/#12/#13/#14/#15/#16/#17/#18/#19. The
#       SSE event types Anthropic ships (message_start,
#       content_block_delta, content_block_stop, etc.) are an
#       industry-standard variant — every other model provider has
#       the same shape. Encoding as a fat record with `kind:
#       string` plus all possible payload fields (tool_name,
#       partial_json, citation_marker, citation_url, usage_tokens,
#       finish_reason, error_message, error_recoverable) is the
#       same fat-record workaround as 9 prior flows. The case for
#       #11 sum types is now overwhelming.
#
#   (c) Backpressure and cancellation are runtime concepts the
#       language cannot reach. "Stop computing if the consumer
#       cancels" is correctness — it prevents pay-for-unused-
#       generation. "Wait for the consumer to catch up" is also
#       correctness — it prevents memory blowout on slow clients.
#       Both are properties of the *channel* between flow and
#       consumer, not of any binding inside the flow body. Today
#       there is no channel — the consumer of a Flow result is
#       outside the language entirely. To support streaming, the
#       language has to admit that flows have consumers and that
#       the consumer's state matters during execution.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Intended flow (NOT expressible in Flow today — uses generator-
# shaped return and event-typed emission):
#
#   flow stream_answer(StreamRequest) -> Stream<StreamEvent> {
#     # initial retrieval (may itself stream sources as they're found):
#     sources = retrieve_with_streaming_emit(it.query)
#       on each Source s ->
#         yield CitationDiscovered { marker: s.marker, url: s.url }
#
#     # main generation loop — each LLM chunk is forwarded:
#     for chunk in generate_stream(it.query, sources, it.max_tokens):
#       match chunk {
#         TextDelta {text} ->
#           if it.cancelled():
#             yield MessageStop { finish_reason: "cancelled" }
#             return
#           yield ContentDelta {text}
#         ToolCallDelta {name, partial_json} ->
#           yield ToolCall {name, partial_json}
#         UsageUpdate {tokens} ->
#           yield Usage {tokens_so_far: tokens}
#         FinishReason {reason} ->
#           yield MessageStop {finish_reason: reason}
#       }
#       check_backpressure_and_drain()
#
#     # post-stream cleanup is implicit; consumer received MessageStop.
#   }
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Friction marks (per the CORPUS_PLAN rubric):
#
#   blocked: #6   streaming / partial results — PREDICTED. SEVENTH
#                 corpus appearance (six organic + this dedicated
#                 stress). The pre-prediction had it at 1. With
#                 seven occurrences across seven distinct domains
#                 (onboarding, incidents, product search, long
#                 research, refinement, decomposition, dedicated
#                 stream), #6 is the single most-undercounted
#                 construct in the prediction table. The Friday
#                 verdict should treat #6 as confirmed load-bearing
#                 by the corpus, not by the stress test.
#
#                 The CORE GAP is the runtime model: `flow X(I) ->
#                 O` returns one O. Streaming wants `flow X(I) ->
#                 Stream<Event>` emitting many Events. This is a
#                 RUNTIME SEMANTICS gap, parallel in scope to the
#                 #12f durable-execution gap from flow #17. Both
#                 ask the language to admit that flows have a
#                 dimension beyond input → return: time, channel,
#                 and consumer state.
#
#   blocked: #11  sum types / variants — TENTH corpus occurrence.
#                 SSE event types are the canonical variant case.
#                 Every other model provider ships the same shape:
#                 ContentDelta, ToolCall, Citation, Usage,
#                 MessageStop, Error. Encoding as `kind: string`
#                 plus a fat record with all possible payload
#                 fields is the same workaround applied across
#                 disputes (#10), gates (#12), RAG sources (#13),
#                 KYC docs (#14), incidents (#15), merchandising
#                 (#16), checkpointed tasks (#17), refinement
#                 steps (#18), decomposition results (#19), and
#                 now stream events. Ten distinct domains. The case
#                 for #11 is no longer a recommendation; it is
#                 corpus-evident.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: BACKPRESSURE / CHANNEL SEMANTICS. NEW
#                 candidate, surfaces only at flow #20. The
#                 language has no notion of a channel between flow
#                 and consumer; therefore no way to express
#                 "the consumer is slow, wait." OpenAI / Anthropic
#                 SDKs and the SSE spec treat this as required for
#                 correctness. Since #20 is the only flow that
#                 needed it, do not promote on count alone — but
#                 record it for any future streaming-language
#                 design pass.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: CANCELLATION / EARLY-ABORT. Related but
#                 distinct from backpressure. The consumer aborts;
#                 the producer must (a) stop computing, (b) stop
#                 billing, (c) emit a final MessageStop with
#                 finish_reason: "cancelled" so the consumer
#                 knows the cleanup completed. Three separate
#                 obligations, none expressible in current Flow.
#                 Same "channel between flow and consumer"
#                 question. Pair with backpressure as the
#                 channel-semantics gap.
#
#   blocked: #3   in-source error handling — mid-stream errors
#                 have nowhere to go in current Flow. The flow
#                 returns one value; if generation errors after
#                 100 tokens already emitted, the caller has
#                 received those tokens already. There is no
#                 "rollback the stream" semantic. The variant
#                 Error event is the production answer
#                 (Anthropic, OpenAI both emit it as a terminal
#                 SSE event) — but the variant gap (#11) blocks
#                 even that workaround.
#
#   blocked: #14  lazy / short-circuit evaluation — fifteenth
#                 corpus occurrence. Stop generation on
#                 cancellation. The producer must NOT continue
#                 computing tokens past the cancel signal.
#                 Different motivation again: not cost-driven
#                 (#3/#6/#7), not policy-correctness (#9), not
#                 fail-fast (#12), but EXTERNAL-EVENT-DRIVEN.
#                 Four documented motivations for #14 now —
#                 strengthens the case that the primitive is
#                 general.
#
#   blocked: #18  (PROMOTED at flow #19) SIDE-EFFECT IDEMPOTENCY.
#                 Fourth occurrence. If a streaming flow is
#                 interrupted and resumed (rare but possible with
#                 server failover), already-emitted events must
#                 not re-emit to the consumer. The "exactly-once
#                 emission" guarantee is the same gap as flows
#                 #17 (checkpoint writes), #18 (per-iteration
#                 emits), #19 (per-node spawn). At four
#                 occurrences across four domains, #18 is solidly
#                 load-bearing.
#
#   blocked: #17  (PROMOTED at flow #17) MANDATORY SIDE EFFECTS.
#                 Sixth occurrence. Each event-emit is mandatory
#                 once it has been generated; the language has no
#                 way to express the emit IS the return.
#
#   blocked: #12  time / scheduling — 12a per-chunk deadlines
#                 (if a model produces no token for 30s, terminate
#                 the stream); 12b pause-and-resume across
#                 connection drops (resume from last sequence
#                 number).
#
#   blocked: #1   multi-branch routing — per-event-kind dispatch
#                 inside the generator body; finish-reason
#                 dispatch (stop / max_tokens / tool_use /
#                 error / cancelled).
#
#   blocked: #5   conditional binding — emit ONLY if event passes
#                 content filter; emit citation ONLY when source
#                 retrieval has resolved; cancellation check
#                 conditional on consumer-state input.
#
#   blocked: #7   sub-flow composition — sub-streams from
#                 sub-flows (retrieval emits CitationDiscovered
#                 events that flow through to the main stream).
#                 Stream composition is a language feature in
#                 streaming-first systems (RxJS, Kotlin Flow,
#                 Java Streams) that Flow has no analogue for.
#
#   blocked: #4   loops / fold over list — 4a generator loop:
#                 `for chunk in generate_stream(...)` is an
#                 iterator-style consumption that the language
#                 cannot express. This is a third sub-shape of
#                 #4: not "map over a known list" (4a flow #4)
#                 and not "while with state" (4b flow #18), but
#                 "iterate over an INCOMING STREAM." Worth
#                 tracking as #4c if streaming gains language
#                 support.
#
#   blocked: #10  optional types — citation_url absent on text
#                 deltas; tool_name absent on content deltas;
#                 finish_reason absent until MessageStop. Every
#                 event variant has a non-overlapping field set.
#                 #11 (variants) is the right fix; #10 is a
#                 symptom.
#
#   blocked: #8   string / numeric expression ops — token counting,
#                 byte-accounting for SSE framing, cost
#                 accumulation per stream. Seventh corpus
#                 occurrence (across seven distinct domains).
#
#   blocked: #15  list-literal construction — thirteenth
#                 occurrence. Accumulating event history;
#                 buffered events on backpressure.
#
#   blocked: #16  aggregation primitives — eleventh occurrence.
#                 Fold events into the final summary text; collect
#                 cited sources across the stream; count tokens.
#
#   blocked: #13  Other: no string literals — event kinds, finish
#                 reasons. Recurring.
#
#   shippable: N — the workflow that compiles below BATCHES every
#                  event into a list and returns it at the end.
#                  This is not streaming; it is the opposite of
#                  streaming. A consumer receiving the result
#                  gets all the events at once after the entire
#                  generation has completed — exactly the
#                  behaviour streaming exists to avoid. The
#                  "[StreamEvent]" return type is the maximum-
#                  degenerate workaround; the runtime model
#                  cannot do anything else. This stub is correct
#                  for any consumer that doesn't care about
#                  intermediate output, which is to say: not a
#                  streaming consumer.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Compilable stub: generate the entire response, batch all events
# into a list, return the list. The fundamental streaming property
# (real-time emission) is lost.

type StreamRequest = { session_id: string,
                     query:      string,
                     max_tokens: int }

type StreamEvent   = { kind:               string,
                     sequence_number:    int,
                     text_delta:         string,
                     token_index:        int,
                     tool_name:          string,
                     partial_json:       string,
                     citation_marker:    string,
                     citation_url:       string,
                     usage_tokens:       int,
                     finish_reason:      string,
                     error_message:      string,
                     error_recoverable:  bool }

type StreamResult  = { session_id:   string,
                     events:       [StreamEvent],
                     final_text:   string,
                     total_tokens: int,
                     status:       string,
                     finished_at:  int }

tool generate_response_stream  (query:      string,
                                max_tokens: int,
                                session_id: string)         -> [StreamEvent]
  effect model("stream-gen-v1")

tool finalize_response         (events: [StreamEvent])      -> StreamResult
  effect pure

flow stream_answer(StreamRequest) -> StreamResult {
  # workaround: this should EMIT events one at a time as they are
  # generated. Instead it returns a list of all events at the end.
  # The consumer gets everything at once. Streaming is structurally
  # absent — this is batched output with a list-shaped name.
  # Counts toward #6 (the entire point of this flow), and toward
  # every channel-semantics concern (backpressure, cancellation,
  # mid-stream errors) which simply have nowhere to go in this
  # return type.
  events = generate_response_stream(it.query, it.max_tokens, it.session_id)

  # workaround: the final-text aggregation is something the
  # consumer would have done incrementally as deltas arrived;
  # collapsing it into a post-hoc tool is fine for the batched
  # case but is the wrong shape for the streaming case.
  result = finalize_response(events)

  result
}
